00:58:41.250 --> 00:58:43.430
and I want to come back to
it, because I did mention

00:58:43.430 --> 00:58:45.140
that electrons have spin.

00:58:45.140 --> 00:58:49.220
And therefore, they also
have a magnetic moment.

00:58:49.220 --> 00:58:52.790
And we call this, just
think of it as some constant

00:58:52.790 --> 00:58:54.530
that we call the Bohr magneton.

00:58:54.530 --> 00:58:55.350
It has a value.

00:58:58.970 --> 00:59:02.900
Well, and if you think
about an atom or a molecule,

00:59:02.900 --> 00:59:06.710
you could just get that by
knowing how many electrons

00:59:06.710 --> 00:59:12.740
are spinning in one direction
more than the other, right?

00:59:12.740 --> 00:59:15.170
So you can just count
how many spin up

00:59:15.170 --> 00:59:18.945
electrons minus how many
spin down electrons you have,

00:59:18.945 --> 00:59:20.570
and multiply that by
the Bohr magneton.

00:59:20.570 --> 00:59:22.320
And that will give you
the magnetic moment

00:59:22.320 --> 00:59:24.530
of the atom or molecule.

00:59:24.530 --> 00:59:25.910
But what would I do for a solid?

00:59:30.000 --> 00:59:31.770
Do I still have it?

00:59:31.770 --> 00:59:32.910
Yeah.

00:59:32.910 --> 00:59:35.820
See, there's the atomic picture
where I could just count.

00:59:35.820 --> 00:59:38.700
And in this case,
the difference is 3.

00:59:38.700 --> 00:59:39.330
Right?

00:59:39.330 --> 00:59:41.050
But now, I've got a solid.

00:59:41.050 --> 00:59:42.050
So what do I want to do?

00:59:47.545 --> 00:59:49.455
What do I want to
look at for a solid?

00:59:49.455 --> 00:59:50.640
AUDIENCE: Density of states.

00:59:50.640 --> 00:59:52.200
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
Density of states.

00:59:52.200 --> 00:59:54.390
And it turns out
that you can plot

00:59:54.390 --> 00:59:58.380
the density of states for spin
up and spin down electrons

00:59:58.380 --> 00:59:59.930
separately.

00:59:59.930 --> 01:00:01.840
And they can be different.

01:00:01.840 --> 01:00:05.660
They can occupy the
two spins differently

01:00:05.660 --> 01:00:09.920
in a more complicated
way, but very much same

01:00:09.920 --> 01:00:13.010
idea as what can happen
in and out of them.

01:00:13.010 --> 01:00:14.630
But it's more
complicated as you get

01:00:14.630 --> 01:00:17.930
these curvy bands and
all kinds of other things

01:00:17.930 --> 01:00:19.470
that can happen in a solid.

01:00:19.470 --> 01:00:24.230
So now, you look at the separate
density of states for electrons

01:00:24.230 --> 01:00:26.210
with spin up versus spin down.

01:00:26.210 --> 01:00:28.400
And that is something that
I didn't talk about yet.

01:00:28.400 --> 01:00:32.300
It's an input
parameter in SIESTA

01:00:32.300 --> 01:00:35.660
that is checked yes
by default. And it's

01:00:35.660 --> 01:00:38.910
called spin polarized,
question mark,

01:00:38.910 --> 01:00:40.170
I think is what it's called.

01:00:40.170 --> 01:00:41.400
Spin polarized?

01:00:41.400 --> 01:00:44.340
I should give the
right intonation.

01:00:44.340 --> 01:00:45.840
And you say yes or no.

01:00:45.840 --> 01:00:47.683
And you say yes, because
that's the default.

01:00:47.683 --> 01:00:49.350
But what are you doing
when you say yes?

01:00:49.350 --> 01:00:51.210
Well, what you're
doing is you're

01:00:51.210 --> 01:00:56.430
telling the calculation to
allow the up and down electrons

01:00:56.430 --> 01:01:00.000
to have freedom
from one another.

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:01.510
That's actually critical.

01:01:01.510 --> 01:01:04.380
So if you didn't
do that, you would

01:01:04.380 --> 01:01:08.820
be simulating the material
with the constraint

01:01:08.820 --> 01:01:11.530
that the up and down
electrons are exactly

01:01:11.530 --> 01:01:12.405
at the same energies.

01:01:15.030 --> 01:01:19.560
So spin polarized,
the reason you

01:01:19.560 --> 01:01:22.470
do calculations that
are not spin polarized

01:01:22.470 --> 01:01:24.960
is because many
systems don't have

01:01:24.960 --> 01:01:29.400
a difference between up
and down electrons, right?

01:01:29.400 --> 01:01:32.160
And they are actually
all the same, right?

01:01:35.040 --> 01:01:38.910
What do I have if
I fill this up?

01:01:38.910 --> 01:01:39.810
What atom is that?

01:01:39.810 --> 01:01:40.790
AUDIENCE: Neon.

01:01:40.790 --> 01:01:43.060
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: It's neon.

01:01:43.060 --> 01:01:46.720
And here, every up electron is
the same as every down electron

01:01:46.720 --> 01:01:49.330
for a given state.

01:01:49.330 --> 01:01:51.200
Everything is the same here.

01:01:51.200 --> 01:01:56.050
So it's not like this up
electron of this p orbital

01:01:56.050 --> 01:01:59.590
wanted to be there, and the
down one wanted to be there.

01:01:59.590 --> 01:02:01.450
That doesn't happen for neon.

01:02:01.450 --> 01:02:04.390
And it doesn't happen for many
systems and many materials.

01:02:04.390 --> 01:02:07.330
But certainly in some
cases, and certainly

01:02:07.330 --> 01:02:10.630
for magnetic materials,
that's what causes magnetism.

01:02:13.450 --> 01:02:17.500
It's that you have a difference
between spin up and spin down.

01:02:17.500 --> 01:02:21.130
And that as you occupy
the density of states,

01:02:21.130 --> 01:02:26.680
literally you get a difference
in the number, right?

01:02:26.680 --> 01:02:29.920
So that's what
causes the magnetism.

01:02:29.920 --> 01:02:34.950
So for many materials, there
is no spin polarization.

01:02:34.950 --> 01:02:37.595
Or in other words,
there is no difference.

01:02:37.595 --> 01:02:39.220
Spin up and spin down
is the same here,

01:02:39.220 --> 01:02:40.990
same here, same here.

01:02:40.990 --> 01:02:45.100
But if it's a magnetic
material, what you'll find

01:02:45.100 --> 01:02:47.380
is that if you plot
the density of states

01:02:47.380 --> 01:02:49.900
separately for spin
up and spin down

01:02:49.900 --> 01:02:54.100
electrons, like in this case
for iron, there's a difference.

01:02:54.100 --> 01:02:57.670
And in fact, the magnetic
moment of that material

01:02:57.670 --> 01:03:01.840
is nothing more than the
integral of that difference.

01:03:01.840 --> 01:03:04.660
Again, you're
integrating the DOS.

01:03:04.660 --> 01:03:09.710
And you're finding something
really cool about the material.

01:03:09.710 --> 01:03:13.265
So that's the same
thing as just counting

01:03:13.265 --> 01:03:15.140
number of up a number
of down, but now you're

01:03:15.140 --> 01:03:19.740
counting it in this very
complex filling of states

01:03:19.740 --> 01:03:20.870
that happens in a material.

01:03:23.900 --> 01:03:26.300
Any questions?

01:03:26.300 --> 01:03:32.510
So if I did a calculation
of iron with spin polarized

01:03:32.510 --> 01:03:38.070
checked no, then you see,
these would be identical.

01:03:38.070 --> 01:03:41.037
And I'd get no magnetism.

01:03:41.037 --> 01:03:41.870
And you can do that.

01:03:41.870 --> 01:03:45.260
You can actually do
the calculation of iron

01:03:45.260 --> 01:03:48.343
